column1: Atoms are made up of three kinds of smaller particles

column1: The number of protons an atom has defines what chemical element it is

column3: hydrogen has one proton and sulfur has 16 protons. Because the mass of neutrons and protons is very similar
column4: and the mass of electrons is very small
column5: we can call the amount of protons and neutrons in an atom its atomic mass.

column1: The word ""atom"" comes from the Greek (ἀτόμος) ""atomos""
column2: indivisible

column4: not

column1: In 1777 French chemist Antoine Lavoisier defined the term element for the first time. He said that an element was any basic substance that could not be broken down into other substances by the methods of chemistry. Any substance that could be broken down was a compound.

column2: English philosopher John Dalton suggested that elements were tiny
column3: solid balls made of atoms. Dalton believed that all atoms of the same element have the same mass. He said that compounds are formed when atoms of more than one element combine. According to Dalton
column4: in a certain compound
column5: the atoms of the compound's elements always combine the same way.

column2: British scientist Robert Brown looked at pollen grains in water under his microscope. The pollen grains appeared to be jiggling. Brown used Dalton's atomic theory to describe patterns in the way they moved. This was called brownian motion. In 1905 Albert Einstein used mathematics to prove that the seemingly random movements were caused by the reactions of atoms
column3: and by doing this he conclusively proved the existence of the atom.

column2: Russian scientist Dmitri Mendeleev published the first version of the periodic table. The periodic table groups elements by their atomic number (how many protons they have. This is usually the same as the number of electrons).
or period

column4: helium

column7: krypton and xenon are all in the same column and have very similar properties. All these elements are gases that have no colour and no smell. Also
column8: they are unable to combine with other atoms to form compounds. Together they are known as the noble gases.

column1: The physicist J.J. Thomson was the first person to discover electrons.  This happened while he was working with cathode rays in 1897.  He realized they had a negative charge
column2: and the atomic nucleus had a positive charge. Thomson created the plum pudding model
column3: which stated that an atom was like plum pudding: the dried fruit (electrons) were stuck in a mass of pudding (nucleus).  In 1909
column4: a scientist named Ernest Rutherford used the Geiger–Marsden experiment to prove that most of an atom is in a very small space
column5: the atomic nucleus.  Rutherford took a photo plate and covered it with gold foil
column6: and then shot alpha particles (made of two protons and two neutrons stuck together) at it.   Many of the particles went through the gold foil
column7: which proved that atoms are mostly empty space. Electrons are so small they make up only 1% of an atom's mass.

column2: Niels Bohr introduced the Bohr model. This model showed that electrons travel around the nucleus in fixed circular orbits. This was more accurate than the Rutherford model. However
column3: it was still not completely right. Improvements to the Bohr model have been made since it was first introduced.

column2: chemist Frederick Soddy found that some elements in the periodic table had more than one kind of atom.

column11: when he developed his theory Soddy could not be certain neutrons actually existed. To prove they were real
column12: physicist James Chadwick and a team of others created the mass spectrometer. The mass spectrometer actually measures the mass and weight of individual atoms. By doing this Chadwick proved that to account for all the weight of the atom

column1: The complex atom is made up of three main particles; the proton

column1: Electrons are by far the smallest of the three atomic particles

column1: The nucleus is in the middle of an atom. It is made up of protons and neutrons. Usually in nature

They solved this by finding a particle called a gluon. Its name comes from the word glue as gluons act like atomic glue
column3: sticking the protons together using the strong nuclear force. It is this force which also holds the quarks together that make up the protons and neutrons.

column3: beta or gamma decay. Nuclei can change through other means too. Nuclear fission is when the nucleus splits into two smaller nuclei

column2: or travel around
column3: the nucleus. They are called the atom's electron cloud. They are attracted towards the nucleus because of the electromagnetic force. Electrons have a negative charge and the nucleus always has a positive charge

column1: The electromagnetism of the nucleus is not strong enough to hold onto their electrons and atoms lose electrons to the strong attraction of smaller atoms.

column2: and many isotopes
column3: have what is called an unstable nucleus. This means the nucleus is either too big to hold itself together or has too many protons or neutrons. When this happens the nucleus has to get rid of the excess mass or particles. It does this through radiation. An atom that does this can be called radioactive. Unstable atoms continue to be radioactive until they lose enough mass/particles that they become stable. All atoms above atomic number 82 (82 protons

column1: There are three main types of radioactive decay; alpha
column2: beta and gamma.

column1: Alpha decay is when the atom shoots out a particle having two protons and two neutrons. This is essentially a helium nucleus. The result is an element with atomic number two less than before. So for example if a beryllium atom (atomic number 4) went through alpha decay it would become helium (atomic number 2). Alpha decay happens when an atom is too big and needs to get rid of some mass.

Beta decay is when a neutron turns into a proton or a proton turns into a neutron. In the first case the atom shoots out an electron. In the second case it is a positron (like an electron but with a positive charge). The end result is an element with one higher or one lower atomic number than before. Beta decay happens when an atom has either too many protons
column2: or too many neutrons.

column1: Gamma decay is when an atom shoots out a gamma ray
column2: or wave. It happens when there is a change in the energy of the nucleus. This is usually after a nucleus has already gone through alpha or beta decay. There is no change in the mass
column3: or atomic number or the atom
column4: only in the stored energy inside the nucleus.

column1: Every radioactive element or isotope has what is named a half-life. This is how long it takes half of any sample of atoms of that type to decay until they become a different stable isotope or element. Large atoms
column2: or isotopes with a big difference between the number of protons and neutrons will therefore have a long half life
column3: because they must lose more neutrons to become stable.

column1: Marie Curie discovered the first form of radiation. She found the element and named it radium. She was also the first female recipient of the Nobel Prize.

column1: Rain boots (or rubber boots) are made from rubber or plastic. Rain boots protect a person's feet from water and rain. People who work on fishing boats and farmers wear rubber boots to keep their feet dry. People who work in chemical factories wear rubber boots to protect their feet from dangerous chemicals.

Winter boots are boots that keep a person's feet warm in cold weather. People in cold countries such as Canada and Sweden wear winter boots during the cold season. Winter boots can be made from many different materials
column2: such as leather
column3: fabric
column4: or plastic. Winter boots are insulated with wool or fur to keep the feet warm. Most winter boots also keep people's feet dry.

column1: Work boots (or ""construction boots"") are designed for people who work in construction or factory jobs. Work boots often have a steel toe cover to protect the person's toes. Work boots are usually made of strong leather
column2: to protect the person's foot from sharp objects or dangerous chemicals. Some work boots have a flat piece of steel in the sole to protect the foot from sharp nails. Many countries require construction workers to wear work boots when they are on a construction site.
